smart pointer:  
Smart Pointers: Use smart pointers wherever you can and avoid using raw pointers. They automatically manage memory and deallocate it when objects go out of scope.

below are the smart pointes used in C++
unique_ptr, shared_ptr & weak_ptr:

In C++, smart pointers manage dynamic memory automatically. unique_ptr provides exclusive ownership, shared_ptr allows shared ownership using reference counting, 
and weak_ptr is a non-owning pointer used to avoid circular references. auto_ptr was deprecated because ownership transfer during copy caused bugs.

auto_ptr:
auto_ptr was the first smart pointer introduced in C++. It manages a dynamically allocated object and deletes it when the auto_ptr goes out of scope.

#include <iostream>
#include <memory>
using namespace std;

class A {
public:
    void show() { cout << "A::show()" << endl; }
};

int main() {
    auto_ptr<A> p1(new A);
    p1->show();

    cout << p1.get() << endl;

    auto_ptr<A> p2(p1); // ownership transferred
    p2->show();

    cout << p1.get() << endl; // p1 is now empty
    cout << p2.get() << endl;

    return 0;
}

